    "location": "US, AZ, Surprise",
    "date": "2019-04-19",
    "status": "Analysis Complete",
    "findings": {
      "summary": "A catastrophic failure occurred at the 2 MW / 2 MWh McMicken BESS facility, owned by Arizona Public Service (APS). The event began with a thermal runaway event inside the lithium-ion (NMC) battery container. Approximately three hours later, as a hazardous materials team opened the container door to investigate, a violent deflagration (explosion) occurred, resulting in serious injuries to four firefighters.[35, 36, 37] The incident became a pivotal case study for the global energy storage industry.",
      "root_cause_analysis": {
        "assessment": "A comprehensive investigation by DNV GL confirmed a five-step failure chain: 1) An internal cell defect (dendritic growth) initiated thermal runaway in a single battery cell. 2) The installed clean agent fire suppression system was incapable of stopping thermal runaway. 3) The lack of thermal barriers allowed the failure to cascade through an entire rack. 4) The cascading failure produced a large volume of flammable off-gases that accumulated in the sealed container. 5) The introduction of oxygen when firefighters opened the door created an explosive atmosphere that ignited.[36, 38]",
        "confidence": "Confirmed"
      },
